<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="140" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Very small, yellowish diving beetles (1.4-2.2 mm for the known species, 2.7 mm with the new one described below) with black markings on elytra. Shape of body globular to elongate, widest in middle, not flattened. 1) Occipital line present; 2) basal pronotal striae present; 3) basal elytral striae present; 4) sutural line on elytron absent; 5) basal epipleural transverse carina absent; 6) clypeus with fore margin narrowly and finely bordered, sometimes unmodified; 7) longitudinal elytral carina on disc absent; and 8) parameres two-segmented.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
Includes 27 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Nilsson, AN" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="10" pageNumber="147" title="A World Catalogue of the Family Dytiscidae, or the Diving Beetles (Coleoptera, Adephaga). Version 1" url="http://www.norrent.se" year="2016">Nilsson 2016</bibRefCitation>
), widely distributed in the Aftrotropical, Oriental and Palearctic regions.
</paragraph>
